    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a decision journal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A decision journal is a written record of significant decisions that captures your reasoning, assumptions, expected outcomes, and emotional state at the time of the decision — before you know the outcome. Reviewing these records against actual outcomes over time builds genuine calibration: you learn where your judgment is reliable, where you are systematically overconfident, and which cognitive biases most frequently distort your reasoning."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should you write in a decision journal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Each entry should capture: (1) the decision being made and the options considered, (2) the key reasoning and assumptions behind your choice, (3) what information you have and what you're uncertain about, (4) your confidence level and predicted outcome, (5) your emotional state at the time, and (6) what you expect to observe that will tell you whether the decision was good. Record before the outcome is known — this is what makes the journal useful."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How often should you review your decision journal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Review individual entries when enough time has passed to observe meaningful outcomes — typically 3 to 12 months after the decision, depending on the type. Conduct a broader pattern review quarterly or annually, looking across all entries for recurring biases, systematic overconfidence in specific domains, and patterns in which types of decisions you make well versus poorly."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do most people who try decision journaling quit?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most common failure mode is recording decisions but never reviewing them against outcomes — which eliminates most of the value. The second is applying the journal only to major decisions while skipping medium-stakes ones where patterns are most visible. The third is recording conclusions rather than reasoning — writing 'I chose X' rather than 'I chose X because I believe A, B, and C, and I estimate a 70% probability of outcome Y.' Reasoning records enable learning; conclusion records do not."
        }
      }
    ]
  })} />

